But, instead of burying Speedy immediately, we had him lie in estate in a shoebox for a week, just to make sure he was dead (we did eventually close the box tho). And thus ends the tale of Speedy, and the reason we no longer own gerbils. (6/end)

As can probably be guessed, Speedy unfortunately did not survive being dropped down the stairs. Mom got the rather fun job of explaining *that* to me and my brother. Of course, we were devastated as only little kids could be. (5/?)

Duchess was freaked out by what she must have thought was a rather extreme reaction to her grabbing a toy, and so did not just drop Speedy but instead *spat* him out, which sent him falling down the staircase to the basement. (4/?)

Speedy, being a gerbil and not the smartest of animals, decided to play dead. My mom heard my bloodcurdling shriek from another room and came running in to see Duchess holding Speedy and me in hysterics. She grabbed Duchess by the scruff and told her to drop Speedy. (3/?)

I had taken out Speedy, who was running over my hands as he often did, when he suddenly made a flying leap for the floor. Once on the floor, he was grabbed by Duchess, who thought he was a toy. She didn’t bite down however, just held him in her mouth. (2/?)

Oh no, I forgot one of the funniest pet stories my family has: the hilarious demise of Speedy.
TW: accidental pet death

This is all to say, not all disabled people are going to look like what you think we should look like, and we should be having these conversations more often than we do.

My age seems to embolden people for no reason to make such comments as “but you’re so young!” Which seems as good a time as any to remind them of something I learned from the great @Imani_Barbarin, you can become disabled at any time. (Go follow her, btw!)

I don’t use a cane (yet) and as I have unfortunately discovered, braces for my elbows and knees do not help with any RA pain. But the symptoms, like neuropathy, pain, and fatigue can still affect me even if it doesn’t look like it.

So it’s #InternationalDayOfPeopleWithDisability and I’m going to resurface from paper writing briefly to remind y’all that not only was I diagnosed with RA this summer after 5 years of symptoms, my RA is still for the most part an invisible disability. I’m also 22.
